valueExpression.name: low-risk
valueExpression.expression: ((%q1-boolean or %q1-boolean.not()) or (%q2-boolean or %q2-boolean.not())) and (%q1-boolean.exists() and %q2-boolean.exists() and %q6a-boolean.exists()) and ((%q6a-boolean-safe and %q6b-boolean.exists()) or %q6a-boolean-safe.not()) and (%moderate-risk.not() and %high-risk.not())

valueExpression.name: moderate-risk
valueExpression.expression: %q2-boolean-safe and %q3-boolean-safe and %q6a-boolean.exists() and ((%q6a-boolean-safe and %q6b-boolean.exists()) or %q6a-boolean-safe.not()) and (%high-risk.not())

valueExpression.name: high-risk
valueExpression.expression: %q2-boolean-safe and (%q4-boolean-safe or %q5-boolean-safe) and %q6a-boolean.exists() and ((%q6a-boolean-safe and %q6b-boolean.exists()) or %q6a-boolean-safe.not()) or (%q6a-boolean-safe and %q6b-boolean-safe)

item.text: Conduct the Columbia Suicide Severity Rating Scale (C-SSRS)

Tip
To assess a client’s level of suicide risk, it is crucial to consider multiple factors, including their C-SSRS results, current stressors, psychiatric history, etc. After administering the C-SSRS, speak with your supervisor about the client to determine next steps.

Example dialogue
"I'd like to ask you some questions about your thoughts and behaviors related to suicide. Understanding how you are feeling will help us get you the most appropriate care. If you feel distressed or upset by any questions, please let me know, and we can work together to make it easier on you, such as taking a break or doing something else. Do you have any questions before we begin?"
I am going to ask you a few questions that might be difficult to talk about but are important for me to assess your safety and the level of support you need.
Everything you say here will be kept private between the two of us, unless you want me to tell someone else or you are in danger.

Tip
The client endorses thoughts about a wish to be dead or not alive anymore or wish to fall asleep and not wake up.
In the past month, have you wished you were dead or wished you could go to sleep and not wake up?

Tip
General non-specific thoughts of wanting to end one’s life or die by suicide (e.g., “I’ve thought about killing myself”) without thoughts of ways to kill oneself/associated methods, intent, or plan during the assessment period.
In the past month, have you actually had any thoughts about killing yourself?

Tip
The client endorses thoughts of suicide and has thought of at least one method during the assessment period. This is different than a specific plan with time, place, or method details worked out (e.g., thought of method to kill oneself but not a specific plan). This includes a client who would say: "I thought about taking an overdose but I never made a specific plan as to when, where, or how I would actually do it, and I would never go through with it."
In the past month, have you been thinking about how you might do this?

Tip
The client endorses active suicidal thoughts of killing oneself and reports having some intent to act on such thoughts, as opposed to "I have the thoughts but I definitely will not do anything about them."
In the past month, have you had these thoughts and had some intention of acting on them?

Tip
The client endorses thoughts of killing oneself with details of a plan fully or partially worked out and with some intent to carry it out.
In the past month, have you started to work out or worked out the details of how to kill yourself? Do you intend to carry out this plan?

Tip #1
Have the person describe the event in detail.

Tip #2
Examples include collected pills, obtained a gun, gave away valuables, wrote a will or suicide note, took out pills but didn’t swallow any, held a gun but changed your mind or it was grabbed from your hand, went to the roof but didn’t jump, actually took pills, tried to shoot, cut, or hang yourself, etc.
Have you ever done anything, started to do anything, or prepared to do anything to end your life?

Tip #1
Explore the presence of lifetime, past year, and past three month behaviors.

Tip #2
Get a detailed timeline about the behaviors.
Were any of these in the past three months?
Discuss with your supervisor before sharing results with the client
A comprehensive suicide risk assessment  includes a thorough clinical assessment. The C-SSRS results are just one part of the suicide risk assessment.
